## Conjecture (CPRR)
- Hypothesis: Alpine and most Linux distros package Guile as plain
  'guile'/'guild' (no version suffix), and FreeBSD packages it as
  'guile3'/'guild3' (because FreeBSD has multiple Guile majors
  installable side-by-side). The Makefile had a Darwin override
  but no general Linux/Alpine override, so the FreeBSD-default
  names broke for everyone except FreeBSD and macOS.

## Validation
- `command -v` is POSIX standard and is in busybox on Alpine, so the
  shell expansion is portable across all CI runners.
- Local Mac: GUILD resolves to /opt/homebrew/bin/guild (correct).
- Tests/check workflow runs on a self-hosted FreeBSD box (per the
  earlier passing runs). On FreeBSD `guile3` is in PATH and
  `command -v guile3` finds it first — preserves existing behaviour.
- Alpine in the Container/build workflow has /usr/bin/guile and
  /usr/bin/guild from the apk guile package — second branch of the
  cascade matches.
- The literal-name final fallback gives a deterministic
  \"command not found\" if neither exists, which is a much better
  failure mode than an empty variable producing a confusing error.

## Refutation / known limits
- This patch only fixes the BUILD step. If the runtime Docker image
  (FROM stage-1) also has the same naming mismatch, the wrapper
  script installed by 'gmake install' would fail. The Dockerfile
  needs a separate audit to confirm — out of scope for this commit.
- We don't validate at make-time that the resolved GUILE/GUILD are
  actually the right Guile MAJOR version (needs 3.0+). If a Linux
  box has guile-2.0 only, the build will silently use it and fail
  later. A `guile --version | grep -q '^guile.*3\\.'` check could
  be added but that's gold-plating for a CI hotfix.

